\begingroup\small
\tzpsection{Definition}
The Gauss linking number is an integer-valued topological invariant that measures the oriented linking of two disjoint closed curves $C_1$ and $C_2$.

\tzpsection{Contextual Meaning}
For closed field-line or flux-tube paths, $Lk$ records whether the paths wind around one another and how that winding is oriented. Continuous deformation without intersection leaves the linking count unchanged.

\tzpsection{Formal Statement}
\[
Lk=\frac{1}{4\pi}\oint_{C_1}\oint_{C_2}\frac{(\mathbf{r}_1-\mathbf{r}_2)\cdot(\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}_1\times\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}_2)}{|\mathbf{r}_1-\mathbf{r}_2|^3}
\]

\tzpsection{Technical Interpretation}
The vector difference $\mathbf{r}_1-\mathbf{r}_2$ supplies separation, the cross product of path differentials supplies oriented area, and the cubic norm normalizes the local contribution before integration over both curves.

\tzpsection{Equation Grounding}
The approved aligned source passage supplies the Gauss linking integral and identifies $Lk$ as the linking invariant for the paired closed paths.

\tzpsection{Interpretive Role}
This entry grounds the topological counting relation that can support later helicity or flux-linkage interpretations without asserting those later physical models here.
\endgroup

\tzpsection{TZP Thesaurus}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.6em,itemsep=6pt,topsep=4pt]
\item \textbf{Gauss Linking Number}: The integer topological count of oriented winding between two closed curves.
\item \textbf{Closed Curve Pair}: The two paths $C_1$ and $C_2$ over which the linking integral is evaluated.
\item \textbf{Topological Invariance}: Preservation of $Lk$ under continuous deformations that avoid curve intersection.
\end{enumerate}
